comments.text:
Well it wasn't technically a date but close enough. It all started when I 
called "Mr. -F" to cancel our 1st date (as I had just accepted a 
relationship with some else) but he was very, very persistent and I was a 
naive Un. 1st year. So I told him I normally eat my lunch at the university 
cafeteria and he could talk to me (NOT A DATE) while I ate/waited for my 
boyfriend to get off work and join me. "Mr. -F" agreed, but then proceeded 
to instruct me (not ask) to ware makeup and a skirt. I internally vowed I 
would never hand my # to a guy I had previously spent <1hr with.
 My new boyfriend laughed when I told him about "Mr. F" and my concerns, 
and half teasingly said he would NOT come to my rescue; "I don't need to 
take care of you". (FYI: he's now an old ex-boyfriend) So when lunch came 
that day I was not really happy to see "Mr. -F" none the less I was polite. 
Despite instructing me to look nice (which I did; stupid afternoon choir 
performance!) he was rather shabby. I was a little confused by this, but 
didn't say anything. We proceeded to chat, in which he asked some questions 
about my eating habits including "do you normally have that much for 
lunch?". I didn't see the harm so I answered them "Well no, I normally eat 
a little more but I'm singing later. But then I don't eat much dinner".
 At about 10mins chatting, he pulls out a paper he wrote and gives it to me 
to read. I had to skim through it a couple of times to make sure I was not 
mistaken because believe what I was reading! It was a paper on how men 
really dig fat chicks more than skinny. ...fat? Fat?! FAT?!!!!! Sure I was 
a little over weight from my year and a half overseas but... no, that can't 
be it, cause no guy is so stupid as to just call a girl 'fat' even when it 
is true, right? "Mr. -F" then proceeded to twist all the answers I gave him 
to basically say I over ate and he thought I was a hot tub of lard. ... ... 
... Oh if glares could kill!!
 With nothing ethical coming to mind that I could do to him (why couldn't I 
just think to throw water in his face!), I got up, said was off to see my 
boyfriend, and left. I may have hide in a ladies bathroom a couple of times 
to make sure he didn't follow me.
 Maybe I'm being too spiteful on the matter, but whatever class he wrote 
that paper for, I hope  "Mr. -F" Flunked! ﻿

The worst set-up I've ever been on:  I'm a 6 foot girl.  A guy I really 
liked named Jake told me he wanted to set me up with his best friend. 
 Let's say his name was Josh.  I figured Josh had to be pretty awesome if 
he was the best friend.  It was a double date, so I went with Jake and his 
date to meet this friend Josh for dinner at the friend's house.  I walk in, 
and met Josh's parents.  Josh's dad was short and came to my shoulders. 
 His mom then walked in the room too, and she was super short as well. 
 Then Josh walked in and we stared at each other in unbelief, thinking, 
"How could someone line us up and not even mention that this girl is 12 
inches taller than me?" Anyway, so it was sort of awkward and we went ice 
skating.  Josh was nice and it wasn't a big deal.  6 weeks later Jake told 
me that Josh was engaged to someone from high school.  Go figure.  He was 
from Orem.  I blame Jake.  He was so stupid.﻿

comments.text:
I invited my friend to go on a double date with my older sister and her 
boyfriend. He and I had known each other for several years so we were 
pretty "close". We had the time of our lives caving, cliff jumping, and 
hiking. Later in the day, my date had failed to tell me he had to be back 
by five. We were two hours away from home and it was four... He had planned 
a date with another girl for that night and didn't have reception to call 
or text her he couldn't come. He was mad at me and I was mad at him for the 
next three hours while my sister and her boyfriend were totally oblivious 
to it. When he got reception his other date broke up with him. I didn't 
know he was in a relationship. Once he did talk to me. He asked me how he 
should make up to her. I gave him the worst advise but he saw right through 
it so the silent treatment continued. Then he didn't have a ride home a 
half hour away. My sister had to drive him home at ten... we had to catch a 
plane at five AM the next day...﻿
comments.author: Tisha Chipman
